abstract = {Reclaimed water, also referred to as recycled water, can provide economic and environmental benefits by meeting demands for new sources of water. An internet survey of 486 Oklahomans indicated that there is acceptance for municipal reclaimed water use and a willingness to pay an additional fee on the standard price charged for municipal drinking water per 1000gallons. The study found higher support for reclaimed water among those who had higher incomes, were male, and rented their homes. In addition, those who supported reclaimed water use policy and believed that reclaimed water is not hazardous were willing to pay more for reclaimed water to conserve municipal supplies. A subset of respondents viewed detailed technical quality data on bacterial standards for reclaimed water versus recreational water bodies; rather than reassuring respondents of the higher quality of reclaimed water, this information made respondents less likely to accept the reclaimed water bid. On average, respondents were willing to pay on average $4.20 and $3.47 per 1000gallons more than current rates for reclaimed water to preserve municipal water supply in the two models estimated without and with the attitudinal variables, respectively.}
