abstract = {Background
Vulnerabilities in social motivation among children with ASD constrain attention and responsiveness to parents and other social partners. When this limited social responsiveness remains uncorrected, it is hypothesized to restrict the quality and quantity of social learning opportunities and ultimately yield negative long-term effects on development. Early intervention efforts that target social motivation may hold promise for correcting this detrimental chain of events.
